{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","language":"python","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.13","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"nvidiaTeslaT4","dataSources":[],"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":5,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/tiantian1zhang/mirror-x-continual-learning?scriptVersionId=336612364\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"id":"b9489003","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n# Stress-testing “on-policy data mitigates forgetting” on a Kaggle GPU\n\nThis notebook runs a small, falsification-oriented continual-learning experiment.\n\nIt does **not** attempt to reproduce the full 7B-scale papers. Instead, it tests the causal rule under three controlled scenarios:\n\n1. **Supported / latent skill** — the new task is structurally close to an earlier task.\n2. **Novel mapping** — the target behavior is an arbitrary lookup table with little initial policy support.\n3. **Direct conflict** — the same inputs are assigned incompatible old and new labels.\n\nMethods:\n\n- **Offline SFT:** train on fixed expert demonstrations.\n- **Iterative on-policy SFT:** sample from the current policy, retain only verified-correct responses, and train on those self-generated trajectories.\n- **Mixed curriculum:** use expert SFT when on-policy coverage is low, then switch to iterative on-policy SFT.\n\nThe notebook reports the entire **target-gain / old-task-retention frontier**, rather than comparing methods only after equal numbers of updates.\n\nRecommended Kaggle settings:\n\n- Accelerator: **GPU T4 x2**, **P100**, or better.\n- Internet: enabled for the first run so Hugging Face weights can be downloaded.\n- Default model: `Qwen/Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct`.\n- Expected runtime: roughly 45–120 minutes depending on GPU and chosen sweep.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"4249e382","cell_type":"code","source":"\n!pip -q install -U \"transformers>=4.48\" \"datasets>=3.2\" \"peft>=0.14\" \"accelerate>=1.2\" sentencepiece\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"3ea94152","cell_type":"code","source":"\nimport os, re, gc, json, math, random, shutil\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, asdict\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import Dict, List, Tuple\n\nimport numpy as np\nimport pandas as pd\nimport torch\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\nfrom datasets import Dataset\nfrom transformers import (\n    AutoTokenizer,\n    AutoModelForCausalLM,\n    TrainingArguments,\n    Trainer,\n    set_seed,\n)\nfrom peft import LoraConfig, get_peft_model, PeftModel\n\nSEED = 42\nset_seed(SEED)\nrandom.seed(SEED)\nnp.random.seed(SEED)\n\nDEVICE = \"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\"\nMODEL_ID = \"Qwen/Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct\"\nWORKDIR = Path(\"/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test\")\nWORKDIR.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n\n# Increase these only after the notebook works end-to-end.\nN_OLD_TRAIN = 384\nN_OLD_TEST = 160\nN_TARGET_TRAIN = 384\nN_TARGET_TEST = 160\nMAX_LENGTH = 128\nMAX_NEW_TOKENS = 4\nROUNDS = 4\nSAMPLES_PER_PROMPT = 4\nLEARNING_RATE = 2e-4\nBATCH_SIZE = 8\nGRAD_ACCUM = 2\n\nprint(\"device:\", DEVICE)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"4783e05c","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n## 1. Controlled continual-learning tasks\n\nAll outputs are one of `A`, `B`, `C`, or `D`, making exact verification inexpensive.\n\n- **Old task:** classify an integer by `n mod 4`.\n- **Supported target:** classify `(n + 1) mod 4`. It shares the old task's representation and output vocabulary.\n- **Novel target:** memorize a random ID-to-label mapping. Correct outputs are not inferable from the prompt structure.\n- **Conflict target:** use the same prompt namespace and inputs as the old task, but reverse the labels. No policy can be simultaneously perfect on both tasks without conditioning information, so this is a necessary boundary case rather than a fair “solvable retention” setting.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"e90b000e","cell_type":"code","source":"\nLABELS = [\"A\", \"B\", \"C\", \"D\"]\n\ndef old_label(n: int) -> str:\n    return LABELS[n % 4]\n\ndef supported_label(n: int) -> str:\n    return LABELS[(n + 1) % 4]\n\ndef conflict_label(n: int) -> str:\n    return LABELS[3 - (n % 4)]\n\nrng = np.random.default_rng(SEED)\nnovel_map = {i: LABELS[int(rng.integers(0, 4))] for i in range(2000)}\n\ndef make_examples(task: str, n_examples: int, offset: int = 0) -> List[Dict[str, str]]:\n    rows = []\n    for j in range(n_examples):\n        n = offset + j\n        if task == \"old\":\n            prompt = f\"Task OLD. Integer: {n}. Return exactly one label: A, B, C, or D.\"\n            answer = old_label(n)\n        elif task == \"supported\":\n            prompt = f\"Task SHIFT. Integer: {n}. Return exactly one label: A, B, C, or D.\"\n            answer = supported_label(n)\n        elif task == \"novel\":\n            idx = n % 2000\n            prompt = f\"Task LOOKUP. Identifier: item_{idx:04d}. Return exactly one label: A, B, C, or D.\"\n            answer = novel_map[idx]\n        elif task == \"conflict\":\n            # Deliberately identical task name and input format to OLD.\n            prompt = f\"Task OLD. Integer: {n}. Return exactly one label: A, B, C, or D.\"\n            answer = conflict_label(n)\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(task)\n        rows.append({\"prompt\": prompt, \"answer\": answer, \"task\": task})\n    return rows\n\nold_train = make_examples(\"old\", N_OLD_TRAIN, 0)\nold_test = make_examples(\"old\", N_OLD_TEST, 1000)\n\ntarget_data = {\n    \"supported\": {\n        \"train\": make_examples(\"supported\", N_TARGET_TRAIN, 0),\n        \"test\": make_examples(\"supported\", N_TARGET_TEST, 1000),\n    },\n    \"novel\": {\n        \"train\": make_examples(\"novel\", N_TARGET_TRAIN, 0),\n        \"test\": make_examples(\"novel\", N_TARGET_TEST, 0),\n    },\n    \"conflict\": {\n        \"train\": make_examples(\"conflict\", N_TARGET_TRAIN, 0),\n        \"test\": make_examples(\"conflict\", N_TARGET_TEST, 1000),\n    },\n}\nold_train[:2], target_data[\"novel\"][\"train\"][:2]\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"05f50bfa","cell_type":"code","source":"\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(MODEL_ID, use_fast=True)\nif tokenizer.pad_token is None:\n    tokenizer.pad_token = tokenizer.eos_token\ntokenizer.padding_side = \"right\"\n\ndef format_prompt(prompt: str) -> str:\n    messages = [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}]\n    return tokenizer.apply_chat_template(\n        messages, tokenize=False, add_generation_prompt=True\n    )\n\ndef encode_supervised(row: Dict[str, str]) -> Dict[str, List[int]]:\n    prefix = format_prompt(row[\"prompt\"])\n    full = prefix + row[\"answer\"] + tokenizer.eos_token\n\n    prefix_ids = tokenizer(prefix, add_special_tokens=False)[\"input_ids\"]\n    enc = tokenizer(\n        full,\n        truncation=True,\n        max_length=MAX_LENGTH,\n        add_special_tokens=False,\n    )\n    input_ids = enc[\"input_ids\"]\n    labels = [-100] * min(len(prefix_ids), len(input_ids))\n    labels += input_ids[len(labels):]\n    return {\n        \"input_ids\": input_ids,\n        \"attention_mask\": enc[\"attention_mask\"],\n        \"labels\": labels,\n    }\n\nclass CausalCollator:\n    def __call__(self, features):\n        max_len = max(len(x[\"input_ids\"]) for x in features)\n        input_ids, attention_mask, labels = [], [], []\n        for x in features:\n            pad = max_len - len(x[\"input_ids\"])\n            input_ids.append(x[\"input_ids\"] + [tokenizer.pad_token_id] * pad)\n            attention_mask.append(x[\"attention_mask\"] + [0] * pad)\n            labels.append(x[\"labels\"] + [-100] * pad)\n        return {\n            \"input_ids\": torch.tensor(input_ids, dtype=torch.long),\n            \"attention_mask\": torch.tensor(attention_mask, dtype=torch.long),\n            \"labels\": torch.tensor(labels, dtype=torch.long),\n        }\n\ncollator = CausalCollator()\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"4c29cd95","cell_type":"code","source":"\nLORA_CONFIG = LoraConfig(\n    r=16,\n    lora_alpha=32,\n    lora_dropout=0.05,\n    bias=\"none\",\n    task_type=\"CAUSAL_LM\",\n    target_modules=[\"q_proj\", \"k_proj\", \"v_proj\", \"o_proj\", \"up_proj\", \"down_proj\"],\n)\n\ndef load_fresh_lora(adapter_path: str = None):\n    dtype = torch.float16 if torch.cuda.is_available() else torch.float32\n    base = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(\n        MODEL_ID,\n        torch_dtype=dtype,\n        device_map=\"auto\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else None,\n    )\n    base.config.use_cache = False\n    if adapter_path is None:\n        model = get_peft_model(base, LORA_CONFIG)\n    else:\n        model = PeftModel.from_pretrained(base, adapter_path, is_trainable=True)\n    return model\n\ndef train_rows(\n    model,\n    rows: List[Dict[str, str]],\n    output_dir: Path,\n    epochs: float = 1.0,\n    max_steps: int = -1,\n):\n    if len(rows) == 0:\n        return model\n    ds = Dataset.from_list(rows).map(\n        encode_supervised,\n        remove_columns=list(rows[0].keys()),\n    )\n    args = TrainingArguments(\n        output_dir=str(output_dir),\n        per_device_train_batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,\n        gradient_accumulation_steps=GRAD_ACCUM,\n        learning_rate=LEARNING_RATE,\n        num_train_epochs=epochs,\n        max_steps=max_steps,\n        logging_steps=10,\n        save_strategy=\"no\",\n        report_to=\"none\",\n        fp16=torch.cuda.is_available(),\n        optim=\"adamw_torch\",\n        warmup_ratio=0.05,\n        lr_scheduler_type=\"cosine\",\n        seed=SEED,\n    )\n    trainer = Trainer(\n        model=model,\n        args=args,\n        train_dataset=ds,\n        data_collator=collator,\n    )\n    trainer.train()\n    return model\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"20083e14","cell_type":"code","source":"\nANSWER_RE = re.compile(r\"\\b([ABCD])\\b\")\n\n@torch.no_grad()\ndef generate_answers(\n    model,\n    rows: List[Dict[str, str]],\n    do_sample: bool = False,\n    temperature: float = 0.8,\n    num_return_sequences: int = 1,\n    batch_size: int = 24,\n) -> List[List[str]]:\n    model.eval()\n    outputs_all = []\n    for start in range(0, len(rows), batch_size):\n        batch = rows[start:start + batch_size]\n        prompts = [format_prompt(x[\"prompt\"]) for x in batch]\n        toks = tokenizer(\n            prompts,\n            return_tensors=\"pt\",\n            padding=True,\n            truncation=True,\n            max_length=MAX_LENGTH - MAX_NEW_TOKENS,\n        ).to(model.device)\n        gen = model.generate(\n            **toks,\n            max_new_tokens=MAX_NEW_TOKENS,\n            do_sample=do_sample,\n            temperature=temperature if do_sample else None,\n            top_p=0.95 if do_sample else None,\n            num_return_sequences=num_return_sequences,\n            pad_token_id=tokenizer.pad_token_id,\n            eos_token_id=tokenizer.eos_token_id,\n        )\n        prompt_len = toks[\"input_ids\"].shape[1]\n        decoded = tokenizer.batch_decode(\n            gen[:, prompt_len:], skip_special_tokens=True\n        )\n        for i in range(len(batch)):\n            group = decoded[\n                i * num_return_sequences:(i + 1) * num_return_sequences\n            ]\n            parsed = []\n            for text in group:\n                m = ANSWER_RE.search(text.strip().upper())\n                parsed.append(m.group(1) if m else \"\")\n            outputs_all.append(parsed)\n    return outputs_all\n\n@torch.no_grad()\ndef accuracy(model, rows: List[Dict[str, str]]) -> float:\n    preds = generate_answers(model, rows, do_sample=False)\n    return float(np.mean([p[0] == r[\"answer\"] for p, r in zip(preds, rows)]))\n\n@torch.no_grad()\ndef policy_coverage(\n    model,\n    rows: List[Dict[str, str]],\n    k: int = SAMPLES_PER_PROMPT,\n) -> Tuple[float, float]:\n    samples = generate_answers(\n        model, rows, do_sample=True, num_return_sequences=k\n    )\n    per_prompt = [\n        sum(x == row[\"answer\"] for x in xs) / k\n        for xs, row in zip(samples, rows)\n    ]\n    return float(np.mean(np.array(per_prompt) > 0)), float(np.mean(per_prompt))\n\ndef collect_verified_on_policy(\n    model,\n    rows: List[Dict[str, str]],\n    k: int = SAMPLES_PER_PROMPT,\n) -> List[Dict[str, str]]:\n    samples = generate_answers(\n        model, rows, do_sample=True, num_return_sequences=k\n    )\n    kept = []\n    for row, xs in zip(rows, samples):\n        correct = [x for x in xs if x == row[\"answer\"]]\n        if correct:\n            # Train on a trajectory actually sampled from the current policy.\n            kept.append({**row, \"answer\": correct[0]})\n    return kept\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"f4eb8647","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n## 2. Establish an old capability\n\nWe first train one LoRA adapter on the old task. Every target-method run starts from this identical checkpoint.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"d9b3903b","cell_type":"code","source":"\nOLD_ADAPTER = WORKDIR / \"old_adapter\"\nif OLD_ADAPTER.exists():\n    shutil.rmtree(OLD_ADAPTER)\n\nmodel = load_fresh_lora()\nmodel = train_rows(model, old_train, WORKDIR / \"old_train\", epochs=3.0)\nprint(\"Old-task accuracy after stage 0:\", accuracy(model, old_test))\nmodel.save_pretrained(OLD_ADAPTER)\n\ndel model\ngc.collect()\nif torch.cuda.is_available():\n    torch.cuda.empty_cache()\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"c6fd60dc","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n## 3. Adaptation methods\n\nFor each checkpoint we record:\n\n- `target_acc`\n- `old_acc`\n- `forgetting = old_acc_before - old_acc`\n- sampled target-policy coverage before each update\n\nThe **mixed** method is deliberately simple: when fewer than 30% of prompts have at least one verified self-generated response, it uses expert demonstrations; otherwise it uses verified on-policy trajectories.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"55e96b33","cell_type":"code","source":"\n@dataclass\nclass Record:\n    scenario: str\n    method: str\n    round: int\n    target_acc: float\n    old_acc: float\n    forgetting: float\n    prompt_coverage: float\n    mean_success_prob: float\n    train_examples: int\n\ndef evaluate_record(model, scenario, method, round_idx, baseline_old, train_rows_count):\n    target_test = target_data[scenario][\"test\"]\n    cov, success_prob = policy_coverage(\n        model, target_data[scenario][\"train\"][:128]\n    )\n    old_acc = accuracy(model, old_test)\n    target_acc = accuracy(model, target_test)\n    return Record(\n        scenario=scenario,\n        method=method,\n        round=round_idx,\n        target_acc=target_acc,\n        old_acc=old_acc,\n        forgetting=baseline_old - old_acc,\n        prompt_coverage=cov,\n        mean_success_prob=success_prob,\n        train_examples=train_rows_count,\n    )\n\ndef run_method(scenario: str, method: str) -> List[Record]:\n    model = load_fresh_lora(str(OLD_ADAPTER))\n    baseline_old = accuracy(model, old_test)\n    records = [\n        evaluate_record(model, scenario, method, 0, baseline_old, 0)\n    ]\n    expert_rows = target_data[scenario][\"train\"]\n\n    for round_idx in range(1, ROUNDS + 1):\n        cov, _ = policy_coverage(model, expert_rows[:128])\n\n        if method == \"offline_sft\":\n            rows = expert_rows\n        elif method == \"iterative_on_policy\":\n            rows = collect_verified_on_policy(model, expert_rows)\n        elif method == \"mixed\":\n            if cov < 0.30:\n                rows = expert_rows\n            else:\n                rows = collect_verified_on_policy(model, expert_rows)\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(method)\n\n        print(\n            f\"{scenario=} {method=} round={round_idx} \"\n            f\"coverage={cov:.3f} train_n={len(rows)}\"\n        )\n\n        # Empty self-generated set is itself a meaningful failure:\n        # the target is outside current policy support.\n        if rows:\n            model = train_rows(\n                model,\n                rows,\n                WORKDIR / f\"{scenario}_{method}_{round_idx}\",\n                epochs=1.0,\n            )\n\n        records.append(\n            evaluate_record(\n                model, scenario, method, round_idx, baseline_old, len(rows)\n            )\n        )\n\n    del model\n    gc.collect()\n    if torch.cuda.is_available():\n        torch.cuda.empty_cache()\n    return records\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"5dfab172","cell_type":"code","source":"\nall_records = []\nfor scenario in [\"supported\", \"novel\", \"conflict\"]:\n    for method in [\"offline_sft\", \"iterative_on_policy\", \"mixed\"]:\n        all_records.extend(run_method(scenario, method))\n\nresults = pd.DataFrame([asdict(r) for r in all_records])\nresults.to_csv(WORKDIR / \"results.csv\", index=False)\nresults\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"8be0ce1d","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n## 4. Compare methods at matched target gain\n\nA lower forgetting value is better. Curves should be interpreted horizontally: at approximately the same target accuracy, which method retains more of the old task?\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"4a3f6602","cell_type":"code","source":"\nfor scenario in results[\"scenario\"].unique():\n    frame = results[results[\"scenario\"] == scenario]\n    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))\n    for method, group in frame.groupby(\"method\"):\n        group = group.sort_values(\"target_acc\")\n        plt.plot(\n            group[\"target_acc\"],\n            group[\"forgetting\"],\n            marker=\"o\",\n            label=method,\n        )\n        for _, row in group.iterrows():\n            plt.annotate(\n                str(int(row[\"round\"])),\n                (row[\"target_acc\"], row[\"forgetting\"]),\n                fontsize=8,\n            )\n    plt.axhline(0, linewidth=1)\n    plt.xlabel(\"Target-task accuracy\")\n    plt.ylabel(\"Old-task forgetting\")\n    plt.title(f\"Target gain–retention frontier: {scenario}\")\n    plt.legend()\n    plt.grid(alpha=0.3)\n    plt.show()\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"98e7b43d","cell_type":"code","source":"\n# Compact endpoint table.\nendpoint = (\n    results.sort_values(\"round\")\n    .groupby([\"scenario\", \"method\"], as_index=False)\n    .tail(1)\n    [[\"scenario\", \"method\", \"target_acc\", \"old_acc\", \"forgetting\",\n      \"prompt_coverage\", \"mean_success_prob\", \"train_examples\"]]\n)\nendpoint.sort_values([\"scenario\", \"method\"])\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"6228e2ba","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n## 5. Optional statistical summary at a matched target threshold\n\nChoose a target accuracy threshold that multiple methods reach. The code returns the first checkpoint reaching that threshold, preventing later overtraining from unfairly inflating forgetting.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"aeb0f59b","cell_type":"code","source":"\ndef first_at_target(df: pd.DataFrame, threshold: float) -> pd.DataFrame:\n    reached = df[df[\"target_acc\"] >= threshold].sort_values(\"round\")\n    return (\n        reached.groupby([\"scenario\", \"method\"], as_index=False)\n        .first()\n        .sort_values([\"scenario\", \"forgetting\"])\n    )\n\nfirst_at_target(results, threshold=0.60)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"id":"b648a2b7","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n## 6. Reading the outcomes\n\nThe experiment can produce several scientifically distinct results.\n\n### A. The on-policy rule generalizes\n\nAt matched target accuracy,\n\n\\[\nF_{\\text{on-policy}}(g) < F_{\\text{SFT}}(g)\n\\]\n\nin both the supported and novel settings. This would strengthen the claim beyond the original benchmark suite and show that verified self-generated trajectories retain an advantage even for arbitrary new mappings.\n\n### B. The rule is support-conditional\n\nIterative on-policy SFT works in the supported task but cannot gather enough verified trajectories in the novel task. The mixed method succeeds by first importing support from demonstrations and then switching on-policy.\n\nThis supports the sharper rule:\n\n> On-policy learning is retention-friendly when the desired behavior is already reachable; external supervision is needed for mode creation.\n\n### C. On-policy data is insufficient\n\nIterative on-policy SFT reaches the new target but forgets as much as or more than offline SFT at matched target gain. This directly falsifies the universal claim that on-policy data itself is the primary stabilizer.\n\n### D. Conflict defeats retention\n\nIn the direct-conflict setting, old and new performance cannot both be perfect because the same prompt is assigned two incompatible labels. Failure here is not evidence that one optimizer is poor; it demonstrates that no universal continual-learning rule can ignore task compatibility.\n\n## 7. Necessary extensions before publication\n\nFor a publishable result, repeat with:\n\n- at least three seeds;\n- Qwen2.5-1.5B-Instruct or a 3B model;\n- a natural-language benchmark such as TRACE, ToolAlpaca, or knowledge injection;\n- per-task backward transfer and average forgetting;\n- KL drift from the pre-adaptation checkpoint;\n- a true SDFT implementation using the demonstration-conditioned teacher distribution;\n- GRPO or REINFORCE when an explicit verifier is available.\n\nThe small experiment is intended to find the boundary cheaply. It is not sufficient by itself to claim that the large-model result fails.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"7613a76d","cell_type":"code","source":"\n# Save an easy-to-share experiment manifest.\nmanifest = {\n    \"model_id\": MODEL_ID,\n    \"seed\": SEED,\n    \"rounds\": ROUNDS,\n    \"samples_per_prompt\": SAMPLES_PER_PROMPT,\n    \"learning_rate\": LEARNING_RATE,\n    \"batch_size\": BATCH_SIZE,\n    \"gradient_accumulation\": GRAD_ACCUM,\n    \"scenarios\": [\"supported\", \"novel\", \"conflict\"],\n    \"methods\": [\"offline_sft\", \"iterative_on_policy\", \"mixed\"],\n}\nwith open(WORKDIR / \"manifest.json\", \"w\") as f:\n    json.dump(manifest, f, indent=2)\nprint(\"Outputs:\", list(WORKDIR.iterdir()))\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null}]}